e Normans, and brought to England by immigrants from the Low Countries and France. It was borne by a Norman saint (  <i>c.</i>1066–1115 ) who became bishop of Amiens. There has been considerable confusion with   Geoffrey ."]},{"name":"Goffin","meanings":["Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): metonymic occupational from German <i>Hopfen</i> ‘hops’. The initial <i>g</i> is due to Russian influence, since Russian has no <i>h</i> and alters it to <i>g</i> in borrowed words and names.","French and Walloon: from a pet form of the personal name   Godefroy  .","French and Walloon: possibly also a nickname from a diminutive of Old French <i>goffe</i> ‘heavy, coarse’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Godefroi d'Arleux was born in 1031, in Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Nicodème d'Arleux, was 27 and his mother, Anne de Wavrin, was 18. He married Adelaide d'Habarcq in 1053. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1089, in his hometown, at the age of 58."},"et":{"1031–1089":"1031–1089","1038–1089":"1038–1089","1054–1109":"1054–1109","1056–1116":"1056–1116","1004–1062":"1004–1062","1013–1069":"1013–1069","1116":"1116","1038":"1038","1004":"1004","1069":"1069","1013":"1013","1056":"1056","1089":"1089","1054":"1054","1031":"1031","1053":"1053","1062":"1062","1109":"1109","Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Arleux En Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1031–1089":"1031–1089","1038–1089":"1038–1089","1054–1109":"1054–1109","1056–1116":"1056–1116","1004–1062":"1004–1062","1013–1069":"1013–1069","1116":"1116","1038":"1038","1004":"1004","1069":"1069","1013":"1013","1056":"1056","1089":"1089","1054":"1054","1031":"1031","1053":"1053","1062":"1062","1109":"1109","Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Arleux-en-Gohelle, Pas-de-C